'''''Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons''''', often referred to as '''''Captain Scarlet''''', is a 1960s British science-fiction television series produced by the [[AP Films#Century 21|Century 21 Productions]] company of [[Gerry Anderson|Gerry]] and [[Sylvia Anderson]], [[John Read (producer)|John Read]] and [[Reg Hill]]. First broadcast on [[ATV Midlands]] between September 1967<ref name="Bentley, 118"/> and May 1968,<ref name="Bentley, 90">Bentley, 90.</ref> it has since been transmitted in more than 40 other countries, including the United States, Australia, New Zealand and Japan.<ref name="Bentley, 119"/> Combined with [[scale model]] special effects, characters are presented in a form of [[marionette]] puppetry that the Andersons termed "[[Supermarionation]]", a technology which used internal [[solenoid]] motors to produce mouth motions [[Lip sync|synchronised]] with pre-recorded dialogue.

Set in 2068,<ref group="e" name="The Mysterons"/> the series charts the hostilities between [[Earth]] and a race of [[Martian]]s known as the [[Mysteron]]s. After a misunderstanding causes human astronauts to destroy their settlement, the vengeful Mysterons declare war on Earth,<ref group="e" name="The Mysterons"/> initiating a succession of return attacks which are countered by Spectrum, an international security organisation. Spectrum boasts the remarkable abilities of its top agent, [[Captain Scarlet (character)|Captain Scarlet]], who comes to possess the Mysteron [[Healing factor|healing power]] of "retro-metabolism". This ability to return to life after suffering fatal injury essentially makes Scarlet "indestructible".<ref group="e" name="Winged Assassin"/>

''Captain Scarlet'', the eighth of ten puppet series that the Andersons produced in the 1950s and 60s, was immediately preceded by ''[[Thunderbirds (TV series)|Thunderbirds]]'' and led to ''[[Joe 90]]'' and the little-seen ''[[The Secret Service]]''. In terms of visual [[aesthetic]], the series represents a departure from the style of ''Thunderbirds'' due to its use of non-[[caricature]]d marionette puppets of [[Realism (arts)|realistic]] bodily proportions.<ref name="HowsWhys"/> Re-run a number of times on British television<ref name="Bentley, 119"/><ref name="Bentley, 122"/><ref name="Bentley, 125"/> and purchased by the BBC in 1993,<ref name="Bentley, 122"/> the series has been the foundation of [[merchandising]] campaigns since its first appearance, leading to the release of items such as toy [[doll]]s<ref name="Marketing"/> and other associated media, including novels<ref name="Titles"/> and [[comic strip]]s in the Anderson-related children's magazine, ''[[TV Century 21]]''.<ref name="Bentley, 102"/>

Compared to its antecedents, ''Captain Scarlet'' continues to be recognised as much "darker"<ref name="Cambridge"/> in tone and less orientated towards [[Children's television series|child audiences]] due to increased levels of violence and themes of [[Extraterrestrials in fiction|extraterrestrial]] malevolence and [[Interstellar war|interplanetary conflict]].<ref name="Lesterdemon"/> The transition in the puppet design has polarised commentators and former production personnel,<ref name="CrimeTV"/><ref name="Archer and Hearn, 151"/><ref name="Peel, 244"/> although the series has been praised for its depiction of a multinational and [[multiethnic]] cast of characters against a backdrop of a [[utopia]]n future Earth.<ref name="Bould, 219"/><ref name="Bould, 220"/><ref name="WomenInSpace"/> Deciding to revive ''Captain Scarlet'' in the late 1990s,<ref name="Bentley, 123"/> Gerry Anderson supervised the production of a [[computer-animated]] [[Reboot (fiction)|reboot]] series, ''[[Gerry Anderson's New Captain Scarlet]]'', which commenced broadcast in the United Kingdom in 2005.

==Plot summary==
{{Main|List of Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons episodes}}

In the [[The Mysterons (Captain Scarlet episode)|pilot episode]], a team of ''[[Zero-X]]''<ref group="n" name="Zero-X">The ''[[Zero-X]]'' and its lander craft, the Martian Exploration Vehicle ("MEV"), had appeared in the first ''[[Thunderbirds (TV series)|Thunderbirds]]'' film, ''[[Thunderbirds Are Go]]''. Production documentation from ''Captain Scarlet'' confirms that the MEV that appears in "[[The Mysterons (Captain Scarlet episode)|The Mysterons]]" is the same vehicle, which places this series in the same [[fictional universe]] as ''Thunderbirds'' (Bentley, 59), which is set in 2065. Spectrum personnel biographies in Bentley's ''The Complete Book of Captain Scarlet'' also place the events of ''[[Stingray (TV series)|Stingray]]'' (set in 2064) and ''[[Fireball XL5]]'' (set in 2063) in this universe (Bentley, 46<U+2013>7, 50).</ref> MEV astronauts investigate the surface of [[Mars]] in 2068 after unidentified radio signals emanating from the planet are detected on [[Earth]].<ref group="e" name="The Mysterons">{{cite episode|title=The Mysterons|episodelink=The Mysterons (Captain Scarlet episode)|series=Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons|credits=Written by [[Gerry Anderson|Gerry]] and [[Sylvia Anderson]]. Directed by [[Desmond Saunders]]|airdate=First broadcast 29 September 1967}} Episode 1.</ref> The source is discovered to be an extraterrestrial settlement, which is attacked and destroyed when the explorers mistake a harmless sensor device for a weapon.<ref group="e" name="The Mysterons"/> The inhabitants of the settlement, the [[Mysteron]]s, are [[sentient]] computers which form a [[Group mind (science fiction)|collective consciousness]] and possess partial control over [[matter]]. The Mysterons use their power of "reversing matter" to reconstruct their complex and declare that they will seek revenge on humankind for the unwarranted aggression.<ref group="e" name="The Mysterons"/>

Reversing matter, or "retro-metabolism",<ref group="e" name="Winged Assassin">{{cite episode|title=Winged Assassin|episodelink=Winged Assassin|series=Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons|credits=Written by [[Tony Barwick]]. Directed by [[David Lane (director)|David Lane]]|airdate=First broadcast 6 October 1967}} Episode 2.</ref> enables the Mysterons to replicate and control any person or object once the original has been killed or destroyed. This ability is used to conduct a "war of nerves" against Earth, which entails issuing threats against specific targets (from world leaders and [[military installation]]s to cities and continents) and then destroying and reconstructing whatever instruments are required (whether human or machine) to execute their plans. The presence of the Mysterons is indicated by two circles of green light (the "Mysteron rings") which trail over scenes of destruction and reconstruction. Although the Mysterons do on occasion manipulate events from Mars, their actions on Earth are usually performed by their replicated intermediaries.

The leading "Mysteron agent", ''Zero-X'' mission leader [[Captain Black (Captain Scarlet)|Captain Black]], was killed and reconstructed in the service of the Mysterons immediately after the incident on Mars and disappeared when ''Zero-X'' returned to Earth.<ref group="e" name="The Mysterons"/><ref name="CBBiography">Captain Black character biography from ''The Complete Book of Captain Scarlet'' (2001), by Chris Bentley, p. 47.</ref> Spectrum, an international security organisation, created in 2067,<ref group="e" name="Flight to Atlantica">{{cite episode|title=Flight to Atlantica|episodelink=Flight to Atlantica|series=Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons|credits=Written by Tony Barwick. Directed by Leo Eaton|airdate=First broadcast 30 April 1968}} Episode 30.</ref> in which Black was a senior officer, mobilises all its personnel, vehicles<ref group="n" name="Vehicles">[[Spectrum Pursuit Vehicle]]s ("SPVs") and Angel [[Fighter aircraft|interceptors]] are two of a number of vehicles that Spectrum has at its disposal. The [[Spectrum Saloon Car (SSC)|Spectrum Saloon Car]] (or "Patrol Car", acronym either "SSC" or "SPC") is used for unarmed land travel, while the Maximum Security Vehicle ("MSV") and "Yellow Fox", an unmarked security transport disguised as a fuel tanker, can be used to protect [[Mysteron]] targets. Additional aircraft include the Spectrum Passenger Jet, the two-seater Spectrum Helicopter and the Magnacopter for transporting larger numbers of people.</ref> and other resources against the Mysterons. With supreme command maintained from [[Cloudbase]], an airborne headquarters hovering at a height of 40,000&nbsp;feet (12,000&nbsp;m) above the Earth's surface,<ref group="e" name="Dangerous Rendezvous">{{cite episode|title=Dangerous Rendezvous|episodelink=Dangerous Rendezvous|series=Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons|credits=Written by Tony Barwick. Directed by Brian Burgess|airdate=First broadcast 9 February 1968}} Episode 19.</ref> Spectrum has outposts in all major cities. It employs operatives of many nationalities, the most senior of which hold [[military rank]]s, are stationed on Cloudbase and answer to the [[commander-in-chief]] of Spectrum, [[Colonel White]].<ref group="n" name="CallSigns">In communications, Spectrum personnel use the call signal "SIG" ("'''S'''pectrum '''I'''s '''G'''reen") as their [[Voice procedure|affirmative code]]. The negative, "SIR" ("'''S'''pectrum '''I'''s '''R'''ed"), is used less often.</ref> While Cloudbase is defended by the "Angels" [[interceptor aircraft]] squadron, the organisation also boasts a fleet of [[Spectrum Pursuit Vehicle]]s ("SPVs") hidden in secret locations all over the world.

[[Captain Scarlet (character)|Captain Scarlet]] becomes Spectrum's principal weapon in its battle against the Mysterons after the events of the pilot, in which the Mysterons threaten to assassinate the [[World government in science fiction|World President]]<ref group="n" name="Politics">In the fictional universe of ''Captain Scarlet'', power from many individual nations has been vested in a [[World government in science fiction|World Government]], which is headed by a president and operates its own military and security forces. Spectrum is a unified operation that is established to provide a more efficient service than these separate bodies, since its work is not hindered by interdepartmental red-tape (Bentley, 43).</ref> as their first act of retaliation.<ref group="e" name="The Mysterons"/> The human Scarlet is killed in a car accident engineered by the Mysterons<ref group="n" name="MysteronPresence">For the pilot episode exclusively, different techniques are used to indicate the Mysteron presence and influence: in place of the Mysteron rings, the destroyed complex on [[Mars]] is reconstructed by a beam of blue light, while the deaths of [[Captain Scarlet (character)|Scarlet]] and [[Captain Brown|Brown]] are preceded by a transition from a full-colour picture to blue [[monochrome]]. The rings make their first appearance in the second episode, "[[Winged Assassin]]".</ref> and replaced with a reconstruction under their control.<ref group="e" name="The Mysterons"/> However, when the duplicate is shot by [[Captain Blue (Captain Scarlet)|Captain Blue]] and falls to its death from a tall structure, it returns to life with Scarlet's consciousness restored and is thereafter free from the Mysteron influence.<ref group="n" name="CSBiography">Mysteron reconstructions, when killed in the television episodes, are normally permanently destroyed. The sole exception to this is Scarlet, who can die and subsequently revive. The character's biography in ''The Complete Book of Captain Scarlet'' (Bentley, 44) states that the Mysterons intended the duplicate of Scarlet to be "indestructible", unlike their other copies of deceased humans.</ref><ref group="e" name="The Mysterons"/> Scarlet's ex-Mysteron body has two remarkable abilities: he is able to sense the presence of other Mysteron duplicates in his vicinity,<ref group="n" name="CSPowers">Scarlet demonstrates this ability in the episodes "Winged Assassin" (production number: 2), "[[Point 783]]" (production number: 5) and "[[Seek and Destroy (Captain Scarlet episode)|Seek and Destroy]]" (production number: 9), but no others. From the episode "[[Spectrum Strikes Back]]" (production number: 10), Scarlet is seen to be unaware of the presence of Mysteron agents when near to them.</ref> and if he is injured or killed, retro-metabolism will [[Healing factor|restore him]] to a state of perfect health. Now able to use suicidally reckless tactics to thwart Mysteron threats, Scarlet repeatedly braves the pain of death in the knowledge that he will recover to face the Mysterons once more.<ref group="n" name="BrownIndigo">During the series, two other Spectrum officers are killed and reconstructed by the Mysterons in addition to Scarlet, but their duplicates do not possess the power of retro-metabolism: Captain Brown in "[[The Mysterons (Captain Scarlet episode)|The Mysterons]]" and [[Captain Indigo]] in "Spectrum Strikes Back".</ref>

As Scarlet and Spectrum defend Earth against the threat from Mars, it is found that Mysteron reconstructions are particularly vulnerable to electricity<ref group="e" name="Operation Time">{{cite episode|title=Operation Time|episodelink=Operation Time|series=Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons|credits=Written by Richard Conway and Stephen J. Mattick. Directed by [[Ken Turner (director)|Ken Turner]]|airdate=First broadcast 17 November 1967}} Episode 8.</ref> and that they are detectable on [[X-ray]]s, to which their biology is impervious.<ref group="e" name="Operation Time"/> Consequently, two anti-Mysteron devices, the "Mysteron Gun"<ref group="n" name="Killing">In "Spectrum Strikes Back", a line of dialogue from Captain Scarlet states that the Mysteron Gun "is the only gun that can kill a Mysteron." The gun fires lethal beams of [[electron]]s and is seen in no other episodes. Episodes both preceding and following "Spectrum Strikes Back" portray Mysteron agents as being vulnerable to conventional means of killing such as explosions (an example of which is in the 11th produced episode, "[[Avalanche (Captain Scarlet episode)|Avalanche]]") or bullets (of which there are many examples, including the 12th produced episode, "[[Shadow of Fear]]").</ref> and the "Mysteron Detector", are developed to aid Spectrum in their fight.<ref group="e" name="Spectrum Strikes Back">{{cite episode|title=Spectrum Strikes Back|episodelink=Spectrum Strikes Back|series=Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons|credits=Written by Tony Barwick. Directed by Ken Turner|airdate=First broadcast 24 November 1967}} Episode 9.</ref> A three-episode [[story arc]] covers the discovery of a second Mysteron city under construction on the [[Moon]],<ref group="e" name="Lunarville 7">{{cite episode|title=Lunarville 7|episodelink=Lunarville 7|series=Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons|credits=Written by Tony Barwick. Directed by Robert Lynn|airdate=First broadcast 15 December 1967}} Episode 12.</ref> its destruction by Spectrum,<ref group="e" name="Crater 101">{{cite episode|title=Crater 101|episodelink=Crater 101|series=Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons|credits=Written by Tony Barwick. Directed by Ken Turner|airdate=First broadcast 26 January 1968}} Episode 17.</ref> and efforts to negotiate with the Mysterons on Mars via a crystal power source, salvaged from the complex, which has communicational capabilities.<ref group="e" name="Dangerous Rendezvous"/> A failed attempt at [[Spy satellite|satellite surveillance]] of the [[Geography of Mars|Martian surface]],<ref group="e" name="Shadow of Fear">{{cite episode|title=Shadow of Fear|episodelink=Shadow of Fear|series=Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons|credits=Written by Tony Barwick. Directed by Robert Lynn|airdate=First broadcast 2 February 1968}} Episode 18.</ref> aborted military conferences<ref group="e" name="The Trap">{{cite episode|title=The Trap|episodelink=The Trap (Captain Scarlet episode)|series=Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons|credits=Written by Alan Pattillo. Directed by Alan Perry|airdate=First broadcast 10 November 1967}} Episode 7.</ref><ref group="e" name="Flight 104">{{cite episode|title=Flight 104|episodelink=Flight 104|series=Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons|credits=Written by Tony Barwick. Directed by Robert Lynn|airdate=First broadcast 1 March 1968}} Episode 22.</ref> and the sabotaged construction of a new [[space fleet]]<ref group="e" name="Noose of Ice">{{cite episode|title=Noose of Ice|episodelink=Noose of Ice|series=Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons|credits=Written by Tony Barwick. Directed by Ken Turner|airdate=First broadcast 12 March 1968}} Episode 24.</ref> hinder Spectrum's plans to return to Mars, and the organisation is unsuccessful on two occasions in apprehending Captain Black.<ref group="e" name="Manhunt">{{cite episode|title=Manhunt|episodelink=Manhunt (Captain Scarlet episode)|series=Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons|credits=Written by Tony Barwick. Directed by Alan Perry|airdate=First broadcast 20 October 1967}} Episode 4.</ref><ref group="e" name="Treble Cross">{{cite episode|title=Treble Cross|episodelink=Treble Cross|series=Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons|credits=Written by Tony Barwick. Directed by Alan Perry|airdate=First broadcast 23 February 1968}} Episode 21.</ref> The penultimate episode of the series includes an all-out Mysteron assault on Cloudbase with the use of armed spacecraft, which is ultimately [[Dream sequence|revealed to be a nightmare]] dreamt by one of the Angel pilots.<ref group="e" name="Attack on Cloudbase">{{cite episode|title=Attack on Cloudbase|episodelink=Attack on Cloudbase|series=Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons|credits=Written by Tony Barwick. Directed by Ken Turner|airdate=First broadcast 7 May 1968}} Episode 31.</ref> The final episode is a [[clip show]] which ends inconclusively with regards to the war between Earth and Mars and fate of Spectrum and the Mysterons.<ref group="e" name="The Inquisition">{{cite episode|title=The Inquisition|episodelink=The Inquisition (Captain Scarlet episode)|series=Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons|credits=Written by Tony Barwick. Directed by Ken Turner|airdate=First broadcast 14 May 1968}} Episode 32.</ref>

==Production==
{{Quote box|quote=I thought we should make a show about the [[Martian]]s, but then there were doubts being expressed by scientists as to whether the so-called [[Martian canal|"canals" on Mars]] were really man-made. Since we were well into pre-production, I came up with the idea of making the Martians invisible, so if they did come up with conclusive evidence that there was no [[life on Mars]], I could say, "Ha-ha, yes there is<U+2014>but you can't see it."|source=[[Gerry Anderson]] (2002)<ref name="Billboard">{{cite journal|title=A&E's ''Captain Scarlet'' Re-Releases will be Red-Hot|first=Jim|last=Bessman|date=6 July 2002|journal=Billboard|volume=114|issue=27|page=56|publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media]]|issn=0006-2510|oclc=421998067}}</ref>|width=17.5%|align=right}}

When talks to find an American broadcaster for ''[[Thunderbirds (TV series)|Thunderbirds]]'' fell through in the July 1966, production for the series' second season ended with the completion of just six episodes at the behest of [[ITC Entertainment|ITC]] financier [[Lew Grade]].<ref name="Bentley, 13">Bentley, 13.</ref> Having overseen [[Gerry Anderson]]'s work since the creation of ''[[Supercar (TV series)|Supercar]]'' in 1960 before going on to buy his production company, [[AP Films]], during the making of ''[[Fireball XL5]]'', Grade was keen for Anderson's programmes to be transmitted abroad and decided that a new concept would do more to attract potential bidders than a second season of ''Thunderbirds''.<ref name="Bentley, 13"/>

As a result of the cancellation, Anderson was required to come up with an idea for another [[Supermarionation]] series. He had once been inspired by the thought of creating a live-action police drama in which the hero would have unexpectedly been murdered halfway through the series and replaced by a new lead character.<ref name="Bentley, 14">Bentley, 14.</ref> Now giving fresh consideration to this idea, Anderson resolved that a selling point for his new series could be a character that can be killed at the end of each episode and resurrected by the beginning of the next. This, coupled with contemporary theories about the possibility of [[life on Mars]],<ref name="Foreword">Foreword to ''The Complete Book of Captain Scarlet'' (2001), by Gerry Anderson, p. 5.</ref> led to the idea of an [[interplanetary war]] raging between Earth and its neighbour and a worldwide security organisation being called on to defend human civilisation. After further thought, Anderson decided that "[[Captain Scarlet (character)|Scarlet]]" would make an unusual codename for this organisation's "indestructible" agent who can come back to life, while "[[Captain Blue (Captain Scarlet)|Blue]]" could be his partner's designation. From this, Anderson reasoned that all the personnel should have colours for names to form the whole "Spectrum" of colours, and decided that someone called "[[Colonel White|White]]" should be the leader of the Spectrum Organisation much in the same way that [[white light]] is composed of, and can be [[Dispersive prism|broken down into]], the colours of the [[spectrum]].<ref name="Foreword"/><ref name="DVDCommentary">{{cite video|people=[[Gerry Anderson|Anderson, Gerry]]|date=2001|title=''"[[Attack on Cloudbase]]": Audio commentary''|medium=DVD|publisher=[[Carlton Communications|Carlton]]}}</ref>

Intrigued by the often-heard phrase "[[Hypothetical types of biochemistry|life as we know it]]", Anderson wanted to set the aliens of his new series apart from the conventional extraterrestrials of 1960s television and cinema. He therefore worked from a basis of "life as we ''don't'' know it",<ref name="Foreword"/> and made the [[Mysteron]]s that were to feature in the series a race of [[sentient]] computers as opposed to organic lifeforms.<ref name="Bentley, 43">Bentley, 43.</ref> Although this is not explicitly stated in the television episodes, the early intention was that the original Mysteron civilisation came from another galaxy.<ref name="Bentley, 43"/> Having established a settlement on [[Mars]] in the distant past, they fled the planet centuries later, abandoning their computer complex.<ref name="Bentley, 43"/>

Contemporary recollections of the Second World War proved to be an inspiration for a number of design aspects. For instance, Anderson recalled that [[RAF]] pilots had found it difficult to counter German attacks during the [[Battle of Britain]], since taking off from the ground meant that it took considerable time to intercept the enemy.<ref name="Teletronic">{{cite web|last=Marcus|first=Laurence|title=Gerry Anderson: The Puppet Master<U+2014>Part 3|url=http://www.teletronic.co.uk/gerryanderson3.htm|work=''teletronic.co.uk''|month=October|year=2005|accessdate=1 October 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080221150836/http://www.teletronic.co.uk/gerryanderson3.htm|archivedate=21 February 2008|deadurl=no}}</ref> He therefore made Spectrum's headquarters an [[airborne aircraft carrier]] called "[[Cloudbase]]".<ref name="Teletronic"/> The Mysteron rings were inspired by an advertisement for the [[Oxo (food)|Oxo]] range of food products, which included an image of the brand name sliding over a frying pan and the outline of a woman's body.<ref name="DVDCommentary"/><ref name="Teletronic"/>

===Writing===
With a provisional series title of ''The Mysterons'',<ref name="Bentley, 15">Bentley, 15.</ref> Anderson and his wife, [[Sylvia Anderson|Sylvia]], wrote a pilot script in August 1966.<ref name="Bentley, 7">Bentley, 7.</ref> This differed significantly from the final draft of the [[The Mysterons (Captain Scarlet episode)|pilot episode]]. Initially, it was decided that the [[Mysteron]] duplicate of [[Captain Scarlet (character)|Captain Scarlet]] would be artificially resurrected by an advanced Spectrum computer rather than reviving naturally, and that thereafter he would no longer be truly human but a "mechanical man" akin to an [[android]].<ref name="Bentley, 15"/> Another early ambition was for each episode to feature a guest star voiced by well-known actor of the day. To this end, the role of the [[World government in science fiction|World President]] in the pilot episode was originally intended to be voiced by the American-born actor [[Patrick McGoohan]].<ref name="Bentley, 17">Bentley, 17.</ref><ref name="Archer, 38">Archer, 38.</ref>

With Anderson serving chiefly as [[executive producer]], the majority of the writing input for ''Captain Scarlet'' was provided by [[Tony Barwick]], who had previously written for the short-lived second season of ''[[Thunderbirds (TV series)|Thunderbirds]]''.<ref name="Bentley, 31">Bentley, 31.</ref> Originally given the role of [[script editor]], Barwick went on to pen 18 of the 32 episodes himself, and was also often required to make substantial changes to other writers' work.<ref name="Bentley, 31"/> While discussing his approach to writing episodes in a 1986 interview, he drew parallels between the premise and characters of ''Captain Scarlet'' and those of ''Thunderbirds'', suggesting, for example, that the Spectrum Organisation was similar to International Rescue and that the character of [[Captain Black (Captain Scarlet)|Captain Black]] was like the earlier recurring villain, [[The Hood (Thunderbirds)|The Hood]].<ref name="Bentley, 31"/>

===Filming===
After a two-month [[pre-production]] period lasting from November to December 1966, filming for the pilot episode, "[[The Mysterons (Captain Scarlet episode)|The Mysterons]]", began on 2 January 1967,<ref name="Bentley, 22">Bentley, 22.</ref> with a budget of <U+00A3>1.5&nbsp;million for the 32-episode series.<ref name="TVHeaven">{{cite web|last1=Marcus|first1=Laurence|last2=Hulse|first2=Stephen|title=''Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons'': A Television Heaven Review|url=http://www.televisionheaven.co.uk/scarlet.htm|work=''televisionheaven.co.uk''|year=2000|accessdate=1 October 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080629052514/http://www.televisionheaven.co.uk/scarlet.htm|archivedate=29 June 2008|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="Teletronic"/> At an average cost of <U+00A3>46,000 per episode, or <U+00A3>2,000 per minute, it was the most expensive Anderson production to date.<ref name="Bentley: Episode Guide, 119">Bentley: ''Episode Guide'', 119.</ref> A month before, Anderson and his team had dropped the name "AP Films" and renamed their company "[[AP Films#Century 21|Century 21 Productions]]".<ref name="Bentley, 22"/> Many of the directors for earlier Anderson series, such as Alan Pattillo, [[David Elliott (director)|David Elliott]] and [[David Lane (director)|David Lane]], had either left AP Films or were involved in the production of ''[[Thunderbird 6]]'', the second ''[[Thunderbirds (TV series)|Thunderbirds]]'' feature film, at the time that ''Captain Scarlet'' was being produced. Although [[Desmond Saunders]] and Lane were available to direct the first and second episodes, while veteran AP Films director Brian Burgess also contributed, the Andersons needed to transfer some of the more junior production personnel to replace the outgoing staff. To this effect, Alan Perry and [[Ken Turner (director)|Ken Turner]] were promoted from the camera operator and [[art department]]s.<ref name="Bentley, 32">Bentley, 32.</ref> Directors drafted in from outside AP Films were Peter Anderson, Leo Eaton and finally Robert Lynn, who had worked as an [[assistant director]] on the 1958 [[Hammer Film Productions|Hammer]] films ''[[Dracula (1958 film)|Dracula]]'' and ''[[The Revenge of Frankenstein]]''.<ref name="Bentley, 32"/>

The [[Slough Trading Estate]]<ref group="l" name="Slough">[[Slough Trading Estate]]: {{coord|51.5244|-0.6250|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-NWP|name=Slough Trading Estate, Slough, Berkshire}} (principal photography and editing)</ref> in [[Berkshire]] had served as Anderson's production base since the filming of ''[[Stingray (TV series)|Stingray]]'' in 1964.<ref name="Bentley, 12">Bentley, 12.</ref> To accelerate production on earlier [[Supermarionation]] series, pairs of episodes had been filmed simultaneously on separate [[sound stage]]s, a practice which continued for ''Captain Scarlet''. Some filming coincided with the production of ''Thunderbird 6'',<ref name="Bentley, 31"/> which was recorded on a separate puppet stage and released in July 1968. Editing rooms, [[post-production]] offices and a preview theatre were housed in a separate building on the Slough Trading Estate; the crew collaborated with the [[Standard Telecommunication Laboratories]] at [[Harlow]] in [[Essex]]<ref group="l" name="Harlow">[[Standard Telecommunication Laboratories]]: {{coord|51.779|0.128|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-NWP|name=Standard Telecommunication Laboratories, Harlow, Essex}} (electronic collaboration)</ref> on the technical and electronic side of the production.<ref name="Bentley, 57">Bentley, 57.</ref>

A third unit, headed by [[Derek Meddings]] and his assistant [[Michael Trim|Mike Trim]], handled [[special effect]]s and [[Scale model|miniatures]] and was tasked with creating all the permanent sets and models to be used from the pilot episode, such as the [[Cloudbase]] interiors and scaled-down [[Spectrum Pursuit Vehicle]]s. A design innovation for this series meant that the noses of the miniature vehicles would "dip" when stopped, to imitate the sudden application of brakes and deceleration on a real-life vehicle.<ref name="HowsWhys">{{cite web|last=Wickes|first=Simon|title=The Hows and Whys of Supermarionation<U+2014>Part 4|url=http://www.tvcentury21.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=81|work=''tvcentury21.com''|date=29 December 2003|accessdate=26 November 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5m00Txsuc|archivedate=13 December 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> The miniature of the Cloudbase exterior, which was six&nbsp;feet (1.8&nbsp;m) in length, proved to be too heavy to be held up with strings and was instead supported by a metal pole.<ref name="Archer, 23">Archer, 23.</ref><ref name="Bentley, 21">Bentley, 21.</ref> To transfer the [[Mysteron]] rings from script to screen, the production team acted on the advice of producer [[Reg Hill]], who suggested that a [[Reversal film|transparency]] be made that could be panned across the puppet sets using a slide projector.<ref name="DVDCommentary"/>

By the time the series started broadcasting on [[Associated Television|ATV]] in September 1967, [[principal photography]] had been completed for the first 20 episodes.<ref name="Bentley, 41">Bentley, 41.</ref> In general, turnaround for completing all the puppet shots for each episode was two weeks<ref name="TVHeaven"/><ref name="Bentley, 34">Bentley, 34.</ref> or 11 working days.<ref name="Bentley: Episode Guide, 119"/> It was initially predicted that all shooting would be wrapped within eight months,<ref name="TVHeaven"/> but filming overran up until late October because of the demands of the ''Thunderbird 6'' shoot.<ref name="TVHeaven"/> While production on Anderson's next Supermarionation series, {{nowrap|''[[Joe 90]]''}}, began in  November <ref name="Bentley, 114">Bentley, 114.</ref> it was not until early 1968 that the last episodes of ''Captain Scarlet'' were edited and prepared for broadcast.<ref name="Bentley, 41"/>

===Music===
[[File:Spectrum motif.png|thumb|240px|Spectrum [[leitmotif]], associated with [[Cloudbase]] and the organisation in general.]]

[[File:Mysteron motif.png|thumb|240px|Four note [[Motif (music)|motif]] used to illustrate the presence of the [[Mysteron]]s. [[Captain Scarlet (character)|Captain Scarlet]]'s [[Variation (music)|variation]], below, emphasises the character's past as a former Mysteron.<ref name="ImageDissectors"/>]]

Music for ''Captain Scarlet'' was composed by [[Barry Gray]], an experimenter in [[electronic music]], who had scored all the [[Supermarionation]] series preceding it. The opening [[title sequence]] theme, "The Mysterons", was rendered electronically and accompanied by a [[staccato]] drum beat to introduce the lead character of [[Captain Scarlet (character)|Captain Scarlet]].<ref name="Bentley, 40">Bentley, 40.</ref> This beat was also used to link scenes within episodes,<ref name="Bentley, 40"/> and to cut to [[Television advertisement|advertisement breaks]],<ref name="Archer and Hearn, 156">Archer and Hearn, 156.</ref> for which it was accompanied by a zooming image of the Spectrum logo as designed by Tony Dunsterville of the [[art department]].<ref name="Archer and Hearn, 156"/> On the subject of the beat, Anderson recalls, "When I went to the recording session, I heard the drum beat he had come up with and I thought, 'Christ, is this all he could produce?' Looking back on it, however, I can see that what he came up with worked very well."<ref name="Archer and Hearn, 156"/>

The [[closing credits]] theme, "Captain Scarlet", underwent significant change after the completion of the first 14 episodes. The first version had been mainly instrumental, with [[vocoded]] interruptions of the words "Captain Scarlet!" provided by Gray himself.<ref name="Bentley, 40"/> This was then revised as a song performed by a London-based pop group The Spectrum, assembled by [[RCA Victor]]<ref name="Archer and Hearn, 157">Archer and Hearn, 157.</ref> as an imitation of the American band [[The Monkees]],<ref name="Bentley, 40"/> who happened to share their name with the organisation that appears in ''Captain Scarlet''.<ref name="Bentley, 40"/>

In addition to the main theme, Gray scored [[incidental music]] for 18 episodes of ''Captain Scarlet'' between March and December 1967.<ref name="Bentley, 41"/><ref name="TVCentury21">{{cite web|last=de Klerk|first=Theo|title=Complete Studio-Recording List of Barry Gray|url=http://www.tvcentury21.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=67:complete-studio-recording-list-of-barry-gray&catid=116:barry-grey&Itemid=182|work=''tvcentury21.com''|date=25 December 2003|accessdate=1 October 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5m00eATOK|archivedate=13 December 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> Musical accompaniment for the remaining 14 episodes was achieved by re-using these completed tracks as well as music from previous Anderson productions such as ''[[Thunderbirds (TV series)|Thunderbirds]]''.<ref name="Bentley, 41"/> In composing his incidental music, Gray made extensive use of two contrasting, yet similar, themes to illustrate Spectrum and the [[Mysteron]]s.<ref name="Soundtrack">{{cite album-notes|title=Captain Scarlet: Original Television Soundtrack|artist=[[Barry Gray]]|year=2003|coauthors=Titterton, Ralph; Mallett, Tim|page=3|publisher=Silva Screen Records|location=London}}</ref> In their notes to the soundtrack release, Ralph Titterton and Tim Mallett suggest that the music is dominated by a "[[Military band|military]] feel", with an emphasis placed on percussion, [[Brass instrument|brass]] and wind instruments, by contrast to the full [[orchestra]]l sound of the ''Thunderbirds'' score.<ref name="Soundtrack"/> With the exception of the four-note Mysteron [[Motif (music)|motif]], Gray generally restricted his use of electronic synthesisers, including an [[Ondes Martenot]], to space sequences, preferring traditional instruments for [[Earth]]-bound action.<ref name="Bentley, 40"/> Captain Scarlet's motif, heard in both versions of the end credits theme and the incidental music, is a [[Variation (music)|melodic variation]] on the Mysteron theme, emphasising Scarlet's history as an ex-Mysteron.<ref name="ImageDissectors">{{cite web|last=Weedon|first=Robert|title=Spectrum is Green|url=http://www.imagedissectors.com/article/69|work=''imagedissectors.com''|date=20 February 2010|accessdate=20 February 2010|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5qO9TFvZH|archivedate=10 June 2010|deadurl=no}}</ref>

Awarding the soundtrack CD release a rating of four stars out of five,<ref name="Allmusic"/> Bruce Eder of the [[Allmusic]] website describes the collection of theme and incidental music as "a strange mix of otherworldly '[[music of the spheres]]', late-50s/early-60s '[[Space age pop|space-age pop]]', '[[British Invasion]]' beat, Scottish [[Folk music|folk]]-inspired tunes, kids-style '[[Mickey Mouse]]' scoring, marital music, light [[jazz]], and light [[Classical music|classical]]",<ref name="Allmusic"/> and singles out both "Cocktail Music", from "[[Model Spy]]", and the piano track, performed by Gray, from "[[The Inquisition (Captain Scarlet episode)|The Inquisition]]", for particular praise.<ref name="Allmusic"/> In his [[BBC Online]] review, Peter Marsh opines that the darker tone of the music is reflective of ''Captain Scarlet'' as a programme featuring realistic puppets and death,<ref name="BBCReview"/> frightening alien villains<ref name="BBCReview"/> and "no laughs",<ref name="BBCReview"/> stating that "dissonant [[vibraphone]] chords shimmer under hovering, tremulous strings contrasted with urgent, [[militaristic]] drums and pulsing brass<U+2014>driving the action ever onto its climax (and, no doubt, a big explosion)."<ref name="BBCReview"/>

{{Infobox album
