The regular puppet cast of ''Captain Scarlet'' was the largest of all the Anderson [[Supermarionation]] series.<ref name="Drake and Bassett, 232">Drake and Bassett, 232.</ref> While earlier productions had emphasised the benefits of futuristic technology,<ref name="Drake and Bassett, 232"/> for ''Captain Scarlet'' it was decided to develop and deepen the cast of characters.<ref name="Drake and Bassett, 232"/> Further to the enhanced [[Realism (arts)|realism]] of the puppet design, voice roles for ''Captain Scarlet'' were, as opposed to ''[[Thunderbirds (TV series)|Thunderbirds]]'' and other predecessors, also intended to be less [[caricature]]d.<ref name="Drake and Bassett, 240">Drake and Bassett, 240.</ref> Anderson biographers Simon Archer and Marcus Hearn note that, between ''Thunderbirds'' and ''Captain Scarlet'', a proliferation of English-accented voices altered the sound of the Supermarionation production and its impression on the viewer.<ref name="Archer and Hearn, 169">Archer and Hearn, 169.</ref>

'''[[Francis Matthews (actor)|Francis Matthews]]''', voicing [[Captain Scarlet (character)|Captain Scarlet]], had previously turned down offers for voice-acting on ''Thunderbirds''.<ref name="Bentley, 23">Bentley, 23.</ref> Matthews claims that [[Gerry Anderson]] went to great lengths to get him to sign on to ''Captain Scarlet'' because of the skilled [[Cary Grant]] impression that he had once used for a radio programme,<ref name="Bentley, 23"/><ref name="Newmark">{{cite news|last=Newmark|first=Russell|title=Outside Edge: Mysterons Beware|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/outside-edge-mysterons-beware-1507965.html|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|location=London|date=1 October 1993|accessdate=22 October 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5m0240aBP|archivedate=13 December 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> and indeed the English actor based the tones of Scarlet on Grant's [[Mid-Atlantic English|Mid-Atlantic]] accent.<ref name="Archer, 43">Archer, 43.</ref> In contrast, Anderson claims in his biography<ref name="Archer and Hearn, 153">Archer and Hearn, 153.</ref> that the impression was Matthews' choice at audition, and that while it was not what had been intended for Scarlet the production team nevertheless elected to use it.<ref name="TVHeaven"/><ref name="Archer and Hearn, 153"/> Matthews' filmography prior to ''Captain Scarlet'' included the [[Hammer Film Productions|Hammer]] films ''[[The Revenge of Frankenstein]]'' (1958), ''[[Rasputin, the Mad Monk]]'' (1966) and ''[[Dracula: Prince of Darkness]]'' (1966).

Matthew's co-star in ''Dracula: Prince of Darkness'' had been '''[[Charles Tingwell]]''', chosen to voice Dr Fawn, the [[Cloudbase]] chief medical officer. Tingwell, who had provided voices for the second season of ''Thunderbirds'' and its first feature film, ''[[Thunderbirds Are Go]]'', had initially been recommended to the Andersons by [[Ray Barrett]],<ref name="Bentley, 29">Bentley, 29.</ref> a fellow Australian actor who had worked on ''[[Stingray (TV series)|Stingray]]'' and ''Thunderbirds''. However, due to theatre commitments, Tingwell could only contribute to the first 12 produced episodes of ''Captain Scarlet''.<ref name="Bentley, 29"/> Also departing after the completion of "[[Shadow of Fear]]" was the voice of [[Captain Grey]], '''[[Paul Maxwell]]''',<ref name="Bentley, 29"/> a Canadian actor who had voiced the character of Steve Zodiac three years earlier in ''[[Fireball XL5]]''.

'''[[Cy Grant]]''', a Guyanese actor selected for the role of [[Lieutenant Green]]<ref group="n" name="Leftenant">"Lieutenant" is generally pronounced in the British manner, {{IPA-en|l<U+025B>f<U+02C8>t<U+025B>n<U+0259>nt|}} ("left-tenant"), by all but the American characters in the series.</ref> (Colonel White's assistant and Cloudbase's main [[computer operator]] and [[Public address|public announcer]]), had been known to the Andersons for singing topical [[Calypso music|calypsos]] on the current affairs programme ''[[Tonight (1957 TV series)|Tonight]]''.<ref name="CGWeb">{{cite web|last=Grant|first=Cy|authorlink=Cy Grant|title=Lieutenant Green and De Anderson CODE<U+2014>Spectrums, Subconscious Connections & Synchronicities|url=http://nestene1.users.btopenworld.com/cygrant/green.html|work=''cygrant.com''|year=2007|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080123195856/http://nestene1.users.btopenworld.com/cygrant/green.html|archivedate=23 January 2008|deadurl=no}}</ref> His casting influenced the decision to accept '''[[Ed Bishop]]''' as [[Captain Blue (Captain Scarlet)|Captain Blue]] (Captain Scarlet's friend and mission partner),<ref name="Starlog">{{cite journal|last=Hirsh|first=David|year=1982|month=February|title=''Starlog'' Exclusive: Commander Straker Speaks! An Interview with Ed Bishop|journal=[[Starlog]]|issue=55|publisher=Starlog Group|issn=0191-4626|oclc=474082490|url=http://ufoseries.com/magazines/starlog55.html|accessdate=17 November 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080225010532/http://ufoseries.com/magazines/starlog55.html|archivedate=25 February 2008|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="MJSimpson">{{cite web|title=Ed Bishop Interview|url=http://www.mjsimpson.co.uk/interviews/edbishopa.html|work=''mjsimpson.co.uk''|accessdate=2 October 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20071029014902/http://www.mjsimpson.co.uk/interviews/edbishopa.html|archivedate=29 October 2007|deadurl=no}}</ref> as Bishop recalled in an interview recorded in 1995: "It was just that a girl in my agent's office happened to be on the ball. She represented this black actor by the name of Cy Grant and Gerry and [[Sylvia Anderson|Sylvia]] wanted to use him ... And the girl said, 'Oh, by the way, Mr Anderson, we've just taken on a new, young American actor'<U+2014>shows you how long ago it was<U+2014>'a new American actor, name of Edward Bishop. And we know how much you like American voices. Would you like to meet him as well?' He said, 'Okay, send him out.' So I went out and auditioned and got the job."<ref name="MJSimpson"/>

'''[[Donald Gray]]''', who had found himself [[Typecasting (acting)|typecast]] after appearing in the lead role in ''[[The Vise|Saber of London]]'', a [[Detective fiction|detective series]], was having to resort to voice work to support his acting career.<ref name="Bentley, 25">Bentley, 25.</ref> The South African actor was selected for three regular roles: [[Colonel White]], [[Captain Black (Captain Scarlet)|Captain Black]] and [[The Mysterons]]. After his mind is hijacked in the [[The Mysterons (Captain Scarlet episode)|pilot episode]], Black speaks with the same voice that the Mysterons are heard to use when transmitting threats to [[Earth]]. For his portrayal of Black and his Mysteron masters, Gray's voice was electronically deepened to produce a haunting effect.

The voice of Captain Ochre was provided by English-born Canadian, '''[[Jeremy Wilkin]]'''. Having served in the role of [[Virgil Tracy]] during the second series of ''Thunderbirds'', Wilkin remained to voice Ochre for the subsequent production. The character of [[Captain Magenta]], meanwhile, was voiced by '''[[Gary Files]]'''. Another Australian actor, Files was a fresh addition to [[AP Films#Century 21|Century 21 Productions]], and was cast for a number of roles in the second ''Thunderbirds'' film, ''[[Thunderbird 6]]'', before progressing to the role of Magenta for ''Captain Scarlet''.<ref name=GFInterview>{{cite web|title=Gary Files Interview|url=http://www.thevervoid.com/media/scarlet_interview.htm|work=''thevervoid.com''|accessdate=3 October 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080626072515/http://www.thevervoid.com/media/scarlet_interview.htm|archivedate=26 June 2008|deadurl=no}}</ref> Like Files, Welsh actress '''[[Elizabeth Morgan (actor)|Liz Morgan]]''' was new to the Anderson productions and voiced the regular characters of Destiny Angel, the lead pilot of the Spectrum Angel fighter squadron, and one of her subordinates, Rhapsody Angel.

'''[[Sylvia Anderson]]''', the voice of [[Lady Penelope]] from ''Thunderbirds'', voiced Melody Angel, while Canadian actress '''Janna Hill''' was given the part of Symphony. The character of Harmony Angel was voiced by Morgan for five episodes before being replaced by Chinese actress '''Lian-Shin'''<ref name="Bentley, 27">Bentley, 27.</ref><ref name="LMInterview">{{cite web|title=Liz Morgan: Interviews|url=http://www.amb-cotedazur.com/Interviews/liz-morgan.html|work=''amb-cotedazur.com''|date=22 December 2007|accessdate=1 October 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5m01uRyxG|archivedate=13 December 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> about one-third of the way through the recording sessions.<ref name="La Rivi<U+00E8>re, 159">La Rivi<U+00E8>re, 159.</ref> Although Lian only provided the voice of Harmony for one episode, "[[The Launching]]",<ref name="La Rivi<U+00E8>re, 159"/> she received billing for 20 episodes.<ref name="La Rivi<U+00E8>re, 159"/>

Supporting character voices were performed by Anderson, Files, Hill, Maxwell, Morgan, Tingwell and Wilkin. Completing the supporting cast were American actor '''[[David Healy (actor)|David Healy]]''' and British actor '''[[Martin King (actor)|Martin King]]'''. Canadian '''[[Shane Rimmer]]''', who had performed the voice of [[Scott Tracy]] in ''Thunderbirds'' and its films, made a number of uncredited contributions in addition to writing for the series. Fellow Canadian '''[[Neil McCallum (actor)|Neil McCallum]]''', who had provided the voice of the character of Dr Ray Pierce in ''Thunderbirds Are Go'', can be heard in four episodes uncredited. Six members of the voice cast would continue their association with the Andersons after ''Captain Scarlet''. Healy would voice the character of Shane Weston in the penultimate Supermarionation series, ''[[Joe 90]]'', while Files would voice Matthew Harding on ''[[The Secret Service]]''. Wilkin, Morgan and King were all given small roles for these final two Supermarionation series, while Bishop appeared as SHADO Commander Ed Straker in Anderson's live-action series, ''[[UFO (TV series)|UFO]]'', which was transmitted in the United Kingdom from 1970.

===Voice recording===
Character dialogue was recorded on a fortnightly basis,<ref name="Bentley, 41"/> with lines for up to four episodes taped at each session,<ref name="Bentley, 30">Bentley, 30.</ref> at the [[Denham Film Studios|Anvil Films Recording Studio]]<ref group="l" name="Denham">[[Denham Film Studios|Anvil Films Recording Studio]]: {{coord|51.5632|-0.4987|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-NWP|name=Anvil Films Recording Studio, Denham, Buckinghamshire}} (voice recording)</ref> at [[Denham, Buckinghamshire|Denham]] in [[Buckinghamshire]].<ref name="Bentley, 30"/> Each actor, regardless of the size of their contribution, was paid <U+00A3>15 15 shillings per episode<ref name="Bentley, 24">Bentley, 24.</ref> with repeat fees.<ref name="Bentley, 24"/> The cast were not given the opportunity to tour the [[AP Films#Century 21|Century 21]] studios in [[Slough]] until all their work was finished<ref name="Bentley, 23"/> and therefore had no visualisation of their characters during the recording itself. This was to the regret of [[Elizabeth Morgan (actor)|Liz Morgan]]: "we all said that we wished we had seen the puppets before doing the dialogue, as it would have been helpful to have something physical to base the voices on. I knew that Destiny was French and that Rhapsody had to be frightfully '[[Sloane Ranger|Sloaney]]', but that was about it."<ref name="Bentley, 27"/>

==Titles and credits==
{{Quote box|quote=The [[Motion picture credits|titles]] on the series were always devised by me. When it came to ''Scarlet'' I was frightened people would say, 'Oh, it's the same old "crash, bang, wallop" stuff again.' So I made a conscious effort to do something totally different. I don't think I necessarily did the right thing.|source=[[Gerry Anderson]] (2001)<ref name="Teletronic"/><ref name="TVHeaven"/>|width=15%|align=right}}

''Captain Scarlet'' episodes, with the exception of [[The Mysterons (Captain Scarlet episode)|the pilot]], incorporate two sets of [[opening titles]]. The first of these sequences presents the [[title card]] and major production team [[credits]]. The camera moves forward through the model set of a run-down, night-time alleyway, forming the [[Point of view shot|point-of-view shot]] of an unseen assassin, who turns a corner only to meet his death at the gun barrel of [[Captain Scarlet (character)|Captain Scarlet]]. The two seven-letter words of "Captain Scarlet" then appear on-screen in time with the seven strikes of the ''Captain Scarlet'' [[staccato]] drum beat composed by [[Barry Gray]]. This opening sequence is accompanied by a [[voice-over]] from [[Ed Bishop]], which states, "The [[Mysteron]]s. Sworn enemies of [[Earth]]. Possessing the ability to recreate an exact likeness of an object or person. But first, they must destroy ... Leading the fight, one man fate has made indestructible. His name: Captain Scarlet." The sequence is intended to demonstrate Scarlet's indestructibility; the assassin fires on the agent with a [[machine gun]], but the bullets have no effect on their target.<ref name="Drake and Bassett, 244">Drake and Bassett, 244.</ref>

A number of variations on this voice-over exist: Bishop's introduction to the pilot is unique to that episode, and runs, "The finger is on the trigger. About to unleash a force with terrible powers, beyond the comprehension of man. This force we shall know as 'the Mysterons' ... This man will be our hero, for fate will make him indestructible. His name: Captain Scarlet."<ref group="e" name="The Mysterons"/> A rare<ref name="Lesterdemon">{{cite journal|last=Pixley|first=Andrew|coauthors=Michael Richardson, Alice Hendry|year=1985|title=Supermarionation<U+2014>the UK Broadcasts|journal=Supermarionation is Go!|issue=14<U+2013>5|publisher=Super M Productions|url=http://lester.demon.nl/superm/broadcastsUK.html|accessdate=6 November 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5m02NT3pI|archivedate=13 December 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> alternative version runs, "One man. A man who is different. Chosen by fate. Caught up in Earth's unwanted conflict with the Mysterons. Determined. Courageous. Indestructible. His name: Captain Scarlet."<ref name="Lesterdemon"/>

Later prints of the episodes feature an additional voice-over<U+2014>a warning from [[Donald Gray]], which states, "Captain Scarlet is indestructible. You are not. Remember this. Do not try to imitate him."<ref name="Lesterdemon"/><ref name="La Rivi<U+00E8>re, 163">La Rivi<U+00E8>re, 163.</ref> This served both to establish the background to the series and to warn younger fans not to take risks by copying Scarlet's exploits.<ref name="Lesterdemon"/><ref name="Cull: Media History, 200">Cull: ''Media History'', 200.</ref> The warning has been placed after the alternative voice-over which starts "One man ...",<ref name="Lesterdemon"/> or else used in isolation, with Gray providing the sole narration for this first opening sequence.<ref name="Lesterdemon"/>

From the [[Winged Assassin|second episode]], another opening sequence, presenting the main puppet cast, runs after the [[Cold open|teaser]] which sets up the plot to an episode. While the Mysterons announce their latest threat against Earth, the "Mysteron rings" pass over the characters in a number of environments to demonstrate the omnipresence of the extraterrestrials,<ref name="Drake and Bassett, 244"/> while Spectrum codenames are credited on-screen. The Mysterons invariably start their threats with the words, "This is the voice of the Mysterons. We know that you can hear us, [[Earthling|Earthmen]]." For Japanese broadcasts, the opening credits were replaced with a montage of action scenes from various episodes, with children singing an accompanying theme tune. This version can be found in the special features of the ''Captain Scarlet'' DVD box set.<ref name="SHJapanese">{{cite web|last=Bishop|first=Chris|title=Japanese Names as Used in ''Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons''|url=http://www.spectrum-headquarters.com/japanese_names.htm|work=''spectrum-headquarters.com''|date=13 February 2008|accessdate=6 November 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5m02gMbFO|archivedate=13 December 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="SHDVD">{{cite web|last=Bishop|first=Chris|title=Merchandising<U+2014>Multimedias: DVD|url=http://www.spectrum-headquarters.com/DVDpage.html|work=''spectrum-headquarters.com''|date=21 February 2006|accessdate=22 November 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080510221055/http://www.spectrum-headquarters.com/DVDpage.html|archivedate=10 May 2008|deadurl=no}}</ref>

The [[end credits]] were originally to be accompanied by images of [[printed circuit board]]s and other electronic components, to fit in with the Andersons' initial idea that the resurrected Captain Scarlet would be a "[[Android|mechanical man]]".<ref name="Bentley, 15"/> In the completed series, the credits are superimposed on ten paintings of Scarlet in moments of mortal peril. The [[instrumental]] version of Gray's ''Captain Scarlet'' end theme accompanies these images in the earlier episodes, but is replaced by the Spectrum pop group's [[Lyrics|lyrical]] version for the later episodes. The closing-credit paintings were created by comic book artist [[Ron Embleton]].<ref name="Bentley, 102">Bentley, 102.</ref><ref name="Prints">{{cite web|last=Wickes|first=Simon|title=Prints of ''Scarlet'' End Titles Available|url=http://www.tvcentury21.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=317:prints-of-scarlet-end-titles-available&catid=71:miscellaneous&Itemid=178|work=''tvcentury21.com''|date=6 June 2005|accessdate=1 October 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5m02CWUql|archivedate=13 December 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> In 2005, the Animation Art Gallery in London released licensed limited editions of the paintings featuring the signature of [[Francis Matthews (actor)|Francis Matthews]], the voice of Captain Scarlet.<ref name="Prints"/><ref name="BBCArt">{{cite web|title=''Scarlet'' Art|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/news/cult/2005/02/11/16980.shtml|work=''[[BBC Online]]''|date=11 February 2005|accessdate=6 November 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5m02GyRcC|archivedate=13 December 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref>

==Broadcasts==
''Captain Scarlet'' officially opened on British television on 29 September 1967, in the late-afternoon slot of 5.25&nbsp;pm, in the [[ATV Midlands]] region. [[Audience measurement|Viewing figures]] for the pilot episode, "[[The Mysterons (Captain Scarlet episode)|The Mysterons]]", were promising at 0.45&nbsp;million.<ref name="Bentley, 118">Bentley, 118.</ref> Five months earlier, on 29&nbsp; April  the series opener had been given a late-night test transmission in the London area.<ref name="Bentley, 118"/> After the start of the [[English Midlands|Midlands]] broadcasts, London and Scotland followed on 1 October,<ref name="Drake and Bassett, 207">Drake and Bassett, 207.</ref> with the [[Granada Television|Granada]], [[Anglia Television|Anglia]], [[Southern Television|Southern]], [[Westward Television|Westward]] and [[Channel Television|Channel]] areas all televising the series by the end of the month.<ref name="Bentley, 118"/> However, it was not until the start of 1968 that the series was being broadcast all across the nation.<ref name="Bentley, 118"/> In the Midlands region, the ratings averaged 1.1&nbsp;million.<ref name="Bentley, 118"/> In 1968, ''Captain Scarlet'' was also screened in more than 40 other countries, including Canada, Australia, New Zealand and Japan.<ref name="Bentley, 119">Bentley, 119.</ref> In the United States, the series was transmitted on [[Broadcast syndication#First-run syndication in the U.S.|first-run syndication]].<ref name="CrimeTV"/><ref name="scifiontv">{{cite web|title=Sci-Fi on TV: Archive List|url=http://www.scifiontv.com/archive_list.php|work=''scifiontv.com''|accessdate=1 October 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5m02nqQFP|archivedate=13 December 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> Meanwhile, only six episodes of the series were transmitted in the Netherlands.<ref name="Drake and Bassett, 282">Drake and Bassett, 282.</ref>

[[Rerun|Repeat runs]] have varied greatly according to region. While Granada, [[HTV]] and [[Tyne Tees]] continued to broadcast the series into 1972,<ref name="Drake and Bassett, 283">Drake and Bassett, 283.</ref> the Midlands received four [[Color television|colour]] re-runs from 1969 to 1974,<ref name="Bentley, 119"/> while in other areas, such as [[Yorkshire]], it was not repeated at all.<ref name="Bentley, 119"/> All 32 episodes were purchased by the [[ITV network]] for broadcast on Saturday mornings between 1985 and 1986,<ref name="Bentley, 119"/><ref name="Drake and Bassett, 286">Drake and Bassett, 286.</ref> with broadcasting in segmented form on the ITV [[Night Network]] in 1987.<ref name="Drake and Bassett, 286"/> A BBC commission led to the series' first simultaneous [[Television network|network]] broadcast on [[BBC2]] starting on 1 October 1993.<ref name="Bentley, 122">Bentley, 122.</ref> On this occasion, the pilot episode attracted an audience of four million,<ref name="Bentley, 122"/> high enough to award it third position in the BBC2 ratings chart for the week of transmission.<ref name="Bentley, 122"/>

[[Remaster|Digitally remastered]], the series resurfaced on BBC Two in the autumn of 2001.<ref name="Bentley, 125">Bentley, 125.</ref> On this occasion, the episode schedule needed to be re-arranged at short notice to avoid offence in the immediate [[aftermath of the 11 September attacks]].<ref name="ToonhoundEntry"/> The second episode, "[[Winged Assassin]]", in which the [[Mysteron]]s destroy and reconstruct a plane to assassinate a world leader, and the third, "[[Big Ben Strikes Again]]", in which London comes under threat from an atomic device, were held back and replaced with the fourth episode, "[[Manhunt (Captain Scarlet episode)|Manhunt]]", due to parallels between the plotlines and events in the real world.<ref name="THound01">{{cite web|url=http://www.toonhound.com/oct2001.htm|title=The Hound<U+2014>October 2001: ''Scarlet'' Faces ...|work=''toonhound.com''|month=October|year=2001|accessdate=26 November 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080409102053/http://www.toonhound.com/oct2001.htm|archivedate=9 April 2008|deadurl=no}}</ref> In the week after the attacks, the ''Captain Scarlet'' section on the [[Carlton Communications|Carlton]] website was also temporarily removed.<ref name="THound01"/>

==Reception==
{{Quote box|quote=''Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons'' should have been one of the most successful puppet shows and it wasn't. I think it was too perfect. There was a lack of humour. It was too mechanical and needed humanising ... <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Gerry Anderson|Gerry]]<nowiki>]</nowiki> always wanted to make the characters a lot more rigid than I did. I wanted to start to give them human flaws, start to make them more important. He was more inclined to make them just say the lines and fit into a rigid pattern, but if you don't care about the characters, it doesn't really work.|source=[[Sylvia Anderson]] (1992)<ref name="SAInterview">{{cite web|last=Turner|first=Stephen|title=Sylvia Anderson Interview (1992)|url=http://www.tvcentury21.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=63:sylvia-anderson-interview-1992&catid=115:production-staff&Itemid=182|work=''tvcentury21.com''|date=25 December 2003|accessdate=3 October 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5m038wH5t|archivedate=13 December 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref>|width=17%|align=right}}

Although ''[[Thunderbirds (TV series)|Thunderbirds]]'' had run to a second series, [[Gerry Anderson]] states that [[Lew Grade]]'s unexpected cancellation of the production led him to assume that there was no possibility of ''Captain Scarlet'' lasting for more than one series.<ref name="Drake and Bassett, 280">Drake and Bassett, 280.</ref> He comments that, "As far as I can recall, I didn't expect it to continue. I simply went to Lew and asked, 'What's the next thing you want us to do?{{'"}}<ref name="Archer and Hearn, 166">Archer and Hearn, 166.</ref>

''Captain Scarlet'' has generally been regarded as much "darker"<ref name="Cambridge">{{cite book|last1=Bould|first1=Mark|editor1-last=James|editor1-first=Edward|editor2-last=Mendlesohn|editor2-first=Farah|editor2-link=Farah Mendlesohn|title=The Cambridge Companion to Science Fiction|chapter=Film and Television|year=2003|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|isbn=0-521-01657-6|page=90}}</ref><ref name="TVHeaven"/> in tone compared to Gerry Anderson's earlier sci-fi series, as Andrew Billen noted in the ''[[New Statesman]]'' when the programme was remade for 2005: "Whereas ''Thunderbirds'' was about rescuing people, ''Scarlet'' was about damnation, the soul of a resurrected man being fought for between [[Captain Scarlet (character)|Captain Scarlet]] and the equally indestructible [[Captain Black (Captain Scarlet)|Captain Black]]. It was Anderson's [[Gothic fiction|Gothic]] period."<ref name="NewStatesman">{{cite journal|last=Billen|first=Andrew|title=Andrew Billen<U+2014>Red-Hot Hero|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/200502210044|journal=[[New Statesman]]|publisher=Spencer Neal|location=London|issn=1364-7431|oclc=35012871|date=21 February 2005|accessdate=1 October 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5m02uMAOq|archivedate=13 December 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> The horror factor of the [[Mysteron]]s has been recognised, with the depiction of the aliens leading to the series appearing at number 82 in [[Channel 4]]'s list programme ''[[100 Greatest Scary Moments]]'' in 2003.<ref name="100Scary">{{cite web|title=''100 Greatest Scary Moments'': Channel 4 Film|url=http://www.channel4.com/film/newsfeatures/microsites/S/scary/results_90-81_2.html|publisher=Channel 4|year=2003|accessdate=1 October 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080625050328/http://www.channel4.com/film/newsfeatures/microsites/S/scary/results_90-81_2.html|archivedate=25 June 2008|deadurl=yes}}</ref> Simon Wickes of the TV Century 21 website suggests that seriousness of the scripts is ultimately due to the [[Realism (arts)|realism]] of the new, accurately-proportioned puppets, and that this aesthetic change also answers for the enhanced realism in the use of [[miniature model]]s.<ref name="HowsWhys"/>

Parallels have been drawn between the series and the [[Cold War]].<ref name="BritishCulture">{{cite book|last=Christopher|first=David|title=British Culture: an Introduction|publisher=[[Routledge]]|location=London|year=1999|page=114|isbn=0-415-22053-X|chapter=Television and Radio}}</ref> Historian [[Nicholas J. Cull]], for example, interprets the "war of nerves" between [[Earth]] and [[Mars]] as a reflection of the strained international relations of the 1960s and compares the "enemy within" scenario of aliens taking control of human beings to such sci-fi films as 1956's ''[[Invasion of the Body Snatchers]]''.<ref name="Cull: Media History, 200"/> Mark Bould has written that the series "seemed in tune with a decade of [[civil disobedience]] and [[anti-imperialist]] [[guerrilla war]]s,"<ref name="Cambridge"/> a view supported by Rebecca Feasey of the [[University of Edinburgh]], who has written that it is one of a number of series that "exploited the fears of 1960s America by presenting civil disobedience and the potentially negative impact of new technologies."<ref name="Masculinity">{{cite book|last=Feasey|first=Rebecca|title=Masculinity and Popular Television|publisher=[[Edinburgh University Press]]|year=2009|page=57|isbn=0-7486-2798-7|chapter=Science Fiction and Fantasy Television: Challenging Dominant Gender Roles}}</ref> Since 2001, similarities have also been interpreted between the series and the 11 September attacks, as well as the ensuing [[War on Terror]].<ref name="ToonhoundEntry"/><ref name="THound01"/>

However, to other reviewers, ''Captain Scarlet'' is a "[[Camp (style)|camp]] classic"<ref name="Rampton">{{cite news|last1=Rampton|first1=James|title=Briefing: Magical Mysteron Tour|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/television--briefing-magical-mysteron-tour-1508077.html|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|location=London|date=1 October 1993|accessdate=3 October 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5m031rXLE|archivedate=13 December 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="SoundandVision">{{cite book|last=Frith|first=Simon|authorlink=Simon Frith|editors=Frith, Simon; Goodwin, Andrew; [[Lawrence Grossberg|Grossberg, Lawrence]]|title=Sound & Vision: the Music Video Reader|publisher=[[Routledge]]|location=London|year=1993|page=66|isbn=0-415-09431-3|chapter=Youth/Music/Television}}</ref> which, according to Bould, relates well to other Anderson productions due to a shared depiction of "a [[utopia]]n future benefitting from [[World government in science fiction|world government]], high technology, [[ethnic diversity]], and a generally positive sense of [[Americanisation]]. They articulate the commonly-made connection between technological developments and economic prosperity."<ref name="Bould, 219">Bould, 219.</ref> He has also discussed the "Euro-cool [[consumerism]]"<ref name="Cambridge"/> of ''Captain Scarlet''. The concept of world government is common to Anderson's work and was inspired by his thoughts on the matter at the time: "I had all sorts of fancy ideas about the future ... we had the United Nations and I imagined that the world would come together and there would be a world government."<ref name="Cull: British Science Fiction Television: a Hitchhiker's Guide, 121">Cull: ''British Science Fiction Television: a Hitchhiker's Guide'', 121.</ref> Peter Wright has similar ideas to Bould on the technological side of the series, noting the "qualified [[technophilia]]" that it shares with ''Thunderbirds''.<ref name="Wright">{{cite book|last=Wright|first=Peter|editor1-last=Bould|editor1-first=Mark|editor2-last=Butler|editor2-first=Andrew M.|editor3-last=Roberts|editor3-first=Adam|title=The Routledge Companion to Science Fiction|year=2009|publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]], 2009|location=Oxford|isbn=0-415-45378-X|page=98|chapter=Film and Television, 1960<U+2013>1980}}</ref>

Since its first appearance, complaints levelled against the series have targeted the camera work, which has been viewed as too static due to the problem of moving the puppets convincingly.<ref name="HowsWhys"/><ref name="Clark">{{cite web|last=Clark|first=Anthony|title=BFI Entry|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/tv/id/455572/index.html|work=''[[British Film Institute|BFI]] [[screenonline]]''|accessdate=3 October 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080516090835/http://www.screenonline.org.uk/tv/id/455572/index.html|archivedate=16 May 2008|deadurl=no}}</ref> The return to a 25-minute episode format as had been the scenario with ''[[Stingray (TV series)|Stingray]]'' and earlier [[Supermarionation]] series, as opposed to the 50-minute ''Thunderbirds'' episodes, has been blamed for a perceived drop in the quality of the storytelling and lack of [[subplot]]s.<ref name="Clark"/><ref name="Peel, 246">Peel, 246.</ref> Concerns have also been expressed about the characters being underdeveloped: in a 1986 interview, script editor [[Tony Barwick]] described the series as "hard-nosed stuff"<ref name="Bentley, 31"/> which lacked humour, and also said, "It was all for the American market and to that extent there was no deep [[characterisation]]. [The characters] all balanced one against the other."<ref name="Bentley, 31"/>

{{Quote box|quote=While it would become a huge success, ''Captain Scarlet'' received a less than enthusiastic reception from critics. It caused a stir among parents, who condemned the show for its realistic carnage, and (some) children who were bemused by its gritty realism.|source=Chris Drake and Graeme Bassett (1993)<ref name="Drake and Bassett, 290">Drake and Bassett, 290.</ref>|width=14%|align=left}}

Science-fiction author [[John Peel (writer)|John Peel]] perceives a drop in quality between ''Thunderbirds'' and ''Captain Scarlet'' in terms of the use of [[special effects]] in relation to richness of the scripting. In this respect, he compares the divide to the commercial disappointment of [[Steven Spielberg]]'s ''[[Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom]]'' (1984) after the success of ''[[Raiders of the Lost Ark]]'' (1981):<ref name="Peel, 245">Peel, 245.</ref> "Anderson made the same mistake that [[George Lucas]] made, assuming that if the [[Special effects|effects]] were praised in ''Thunderbirds'', the public wanted a show with more effects."<ref name="Peel, 245"/> Peel also turns attention to the nature of Captain Scarlet himself, suggesting that Anderson's conception of an indestructible hero who can unfailingly return to life after death made the conclusions to plotlines too predictable.<ref name="Peel, 246">Peel, 246.</ref> He also notes his concern that Scarlet, who is often seen to risk his life to foil Mysteron plots, provided a poor role model for an impressionable target audience of children.<ref name="Peel, 246"/>

Although seen as a [[Cult following|cult]] series by some critics,<ref name="BritYouthTV">{{cite book|last=Lury|first=Karen|title=British Youth Television: Cynicism and Enchantment|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|year=2001|page=119|isbn=0-19-815970-6|chapter=The 'Television Presenter': the Post-Modern Performer}}</ref> ''Captain Scarlet'' ranked 33rd in a 2007 ''[[Radio Times]]'' poll to determine the greatest sci-fi series of all time.<ref name="RadioTimes">{{cite web|title=''Radio Times'': Sci-Fi Survey results|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/content/features/sci-fi-survey/|work=''[[Radio Times|radiotimes.com]]''|year=2007|accessdate=1 October 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5lzzY1ihB|archivedate=13 December 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> Despite concerns that it is not a true "[[Children's television series|children's]]" television series because of its "dark" tone and level of violence,<ref name="Lesterdemon"/><ref name="h2g2"/> it achieved 51st position in Channel 4's 2001 list programme ''[[100 Greatest Kids' TV shows|100 Greatest Kids' TV Shows]]''.<ref name="100Kids">{{cite web|title=''100 Greatest Kids' TV Shows'': Results|url=http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/G/greatest/kidstv/results.html|publisher=Channel 4|year=2001|accessdate=28 October 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080803013457/http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/G/greatest/kidstv/results.html|archivedate=3 August 2008|deadurl=no}}</ref> Considering ''Captain Scarlet'' alongside its immediate predecessor, ''Thunderbirds'', Gerry Anderson's personal verdict is unambiguous: "Nothing was as successful as ''Thunderbirds''. ''Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons'' was very successful, but once you've had a smash hit, everything tends to look less successful in comparison."<ref name="Bentley: Thunderbirds, 41">{{cite book|last1=Bentley|first1=Chris|title=The Complete Book of Thunderbirds|publisher=[[Carlton Books]]|location=London|edition=2|year=2005|origyear=2000|isbn=1-84222-454-5|page=41}}</ref>

===Puppets===
On the subject of [[Sylvia Anderson]]'s costume design, critic Mark Bould praises the "commitment to fashion" evident throughout the Anderson series, but particularly lauds the design of the Spectrum Angel uniforms.<ref name="Bould, 220">Bould, 220.</ref> Meanwhile, the [[Realism (arts)|realistic]] design of the new puppets has been praised by commentators such as Vincent Terrace<ref name="CrimeTV">{{cite book|last=Terrace|first=Vincent|title=Crime Fighting Heroes of Television: Over 10,000 Facts from 151 Shows, 1949<U+2013>2001|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|location=North Carolina|year=2002|page=43|isbn=0-7864-1395-6}}</ref> and criticised by others. Some members of the production team perceived a lack of charm in comparison to the earlier puppets due to the more natural proportions that were now being used.<ref name="Bentley, 14"/> Director [[David Lane (director)|David Lane]]'s initial thoughts on a prototype, produced by head of puppets John Brown,<ref name="Archer and Hearn, 151"/> were, "it was as if there was a little dead person in [the box] ... because it was perfect in all its proportions it just looked odd."<ref name="Bentley, 14"/> Brown remembers presenting the prototype alongside the [[Lady Penelope]] puppet from ''[[Thunderbirds (TV series)|Thunderbirds]]'' and gauging the response from production staff,<ref name="Archer and Hearn, 151"/> stating, "when they saw it, some people were horrified by the difference. Some didn't like it, some did."<ref name="Archer and Hearn, 151"/><ref name="Teletronic"/> Critics have highlighted the sacrifice of facial expression in favour of a realistic design,<ref name="h2g2">{{cite web|title=''Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons'' <U+2014> Background to the TV Series|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/h2g2/A786486|work=''[[BBC Online]]''|date=12 August 2002|accessdate=1 October 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070806034845/http://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/h2g2/A786486|archivedate=6 August 2007|deadurl=no}}</ref> a consequence on which Terry Curtis elaborates:

<blockquote>
The changes of expression on those puppets had to be perfect and in no way exaggerated like the old ones were. I remember when [fellow puppet designer] Tim Cooksey did [[Colonel White]], he had a lot of trouble doing different expressions as the face was just so realistic. I had a similar problem with [[Captain Blue (Captain Scarlet)|Captain Blue]]. I remember I did a Blue "smiler" head and people could hardly tell the difference between that and the normal one.<ref name="Bentley, 16"/>
</blockquote>

Sculptor John Blundall has referred to the new puppet design as "ridiculous",<ref name="Teletronic"/><ref name="Archer and Hearn, 152">Archer and Hearn, 152.</ref> denouncing Anderson's attempts to have the puppets appear more life-like for the reason that, in his view, "We always try to do with puppets what you can't do with humans."<ref name="Archer and Hearn, 152"/> Stating a preference for the ''Thunderbirds''-era design,<ref name="Archer and Hearn, 152"/> Blundall agrees that the transition from [[caricature]] to realism led to a reduction in "character and personality",<ref name="Archer and Hearn, 152"/> asserting that "If the puppet appears completely natural, the audience no longer has to use its imagination."<ref name="Archer and Hearn, 152"/> In response, Anderson himself states that he pushed for the decision to reshape the puppets to satisfy viewers,<ref name="Archer and Hearn, 152"/> summarising the development as not "a case of moving to a new technique, but more a case of incorporating new ideas with existing methods."<ref name="Archer and Hearn, 152"/>

Summing up ''Captain Scarlet'', in comparison to ''Thunderbirds'', as "better puppets, bigger [[Action (fiction)|action]] and a huge step backwards in stories",<ref name="Peel, 244">Peel, 244.</ref> [[John Peel (writer)|Peel]] disputes the claim that the next generation of [[Supermarionation]] puppets constitute a failure on the part of the series,<ref name="Peel, 245"/> arguing that the increased realism did not deter viewers who had been familiar with the earlier design.<ref name="Peel, 245"/> Although he suggests that the [[characterisation]]s became less endearing,<ref name="Peel, 245"/> Peel's attribution of the reduced believability of ''Captain Scarlet'' is to a perceived over-emphasis on the visual and [[Special effects|effects]]-led aspects to the series at the expense of its human side.<ref name="Peel, 245"/>

===Race, gender and symbolism===
{{Quote box|quote=When I made ''[[Supercar (TV series)|Supercar]]'' for [[Associated Television|ATV]], we put a number of black characters in an episode because the story demanded it. ATV had an American advisor at the time, and he made us take out every black character and replace them with white characters and white voices. He said he would not be able to sell it to stations in the [[Southern United States|South]] because of the black characters ... I was always very anxious to promote racial harmony, so as soon as people had become more sensible I took advantage of it.|source=[[Gerry Anderson]] (1993)<ref name="Drake and Bassett, 204">Drake and Bassett, 204.</ref>|width=16.5%|align=right}}

''Captain Scarlet'' became involved in the [[black-and-white dualism]] debate during its 1993 British repeat run for its use of the codenames "White" to designate the head of Spectrum, [[Colonel White]], and "Black" for the villainous [[Captain Black (Captain Scarlet)|Captain Black]].<ref name="Bentley, 122"/><ref name="La Rivi<U+00E8>re, 160">La Rivi<U+00E8>re, 160.</ref> [[Gerry Anderson]] defended his series against the accusations of [[racism]] and [[political incorrectness]] by reminding critics that the Spectrum characters of [[Lieutenant Green]], Melody Angel and Harmony Angel play heroic roles despite being of either black or Asian descent.<ref name="Bentley, 122"/> Green, in particular, is the only leading male black character to appear in an Anderson production.<ref name="Archer, 32iii">Archer, 32iii.</ref>

In academic works, the diversity of the Spectrum personnel in terms of both race and gender has been viewed highly.<ref name="WomenInSpace">{{cite book|last1=Shayler|first1=David|authorlink1=David Shayler|last2=Moule|first2=Ian A.|title=Women in Space: Following Valentina|publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media]]|year=2005|page=xvii|isbn=1-85233-744-3}}</ref> Bould, for example, mentions "''Captain Scarlet''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s beautiful, [[multiethnic]], female Angel fighter pilots"<ref name="Bould, 220"/> and "secondary roles played by capable women."<ref name="Bould, 220"/> In an interview conducted in 2003, Anderson commented on how he and his production team made an effort to include [[ethnic minorities]] in the series: "... I think people who make television programmes have a responsibility, particularly when children are watching avidly and you know their minds can be affected almost irreversibly as they grow up. We were very conscious of introducing different [[ethnic background]]s."<ref name="Cull: British Science Fiction Television: a Hitchhiker's Guide, 127">Cull: ''British Science Fiction Television: a Hitchhiker's Guide'', 127.</ref>

Guyanese actor [[Cy Grant]], who voiced Green and saw the series as having positive multicultural value,<ref name="CGWeb"/><ref name="La Rivi<U+00E8>re, 160"/> has also noted the [[allegorical]] nature of ''Captain Scarlet''.<ref name="CGWeb"/> Christian symbolism is heavily implied, with Colonel White as [[God in Christianity|God]], Captain Black as the [[Christian teaching about the Devil|Devil]], [[Captain Scarlet (character)|Captain Scarlet]] as [[Christ]], [[Cloudbase]] as [[Heaven#In Christianity|Heaven]], and characters codenamed "the [[Angel#Christianity|Angels]]",<ref name="CGWeb"/><ref name="La Rivi<U+00E8>re, 160"/> but Grant also mentions the idea of Lieutenant Green as an African trickster hero.<ref name="CGWeb"/> On dualism, he suggests that, "the '[[darkness]]' of the [[Mysteron]]s is most easily seen as the psychological rift<U+2014>the struggle of [[Good and evil|'good' and 'evil']] <U+2014> of the [[Western world]] as personified by Colonel White and his team. Dark and [[Light (theology)|light]] are but aspects of each other. Incidentally, green is the colour of nature that can heal that rift."<ref name="La Rivi<U+00E8>re, 160"/>

==Other media==
Since the 1960s, associated [[merchandise]] has complemented the ''Captain Scarlet'' television episodes, examples of which range from children's products such as [[doll]]s<ref name="Marketing">{{cite news|last1=Jones|first1=Helen|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/nostalgia-is-the-bestselling-game-of-all-marketing-captain-scarlet-and-action-man-are-among-the-successful-new-toys-this-christmas-that-will-be-familiar-to-many-parents-1467013.html|title=Nostalgia is the Best-Selling Game of All: Marketing Captain Scarlet and Action Man are Among the Successful "New" Toys this Christmas that will be Familiar to Many Parents|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|location=London|date=12 December 1993|accessdate=19 February 2010|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5nf4eItBQ|archivedate=19 February 2010|deadurl=no}}</ref> to a [[Vehicular combat game|driving-based]] video game, titled ''Captain Scarlet'', which was released for the [[PlayStation 2]] gaming platform in 2006.<ref name="Blast">{{cite web|title=Blast! ''Captain Scarlet''|work=''blast-games.com''|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080419011218/http://www.blast-games.com/en/product.asp?pid=422|archivedate=19 April 2008|accessdate=19 February 2010|deadurl=yes}}</ref><ref name="Gamespot">{{cite web|title=''Captain Scarlet'' Tech Info|url=http://uk.gamespot.com/ps2/adventure/captainscarlet/tech_info.html|work=''[[GameSpot]]''|accessdate=19 February 2010|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5qO9iSdj9|archivedate=10 June 2010|deadurl=no}}</ref>

===Audio adventures===
To accompany the television episodes, [[AP Films#Century 21|Century 21]] released five further ''Captain Scarlet'' stories as [[vinyl record]] [[Extended play|EP]]s, each running to approximately 21 minutes,<ref name="Bentley, 93">Bentley, 93.</ref> and starring the episode voice actors,<ref name="Bentley, 93"/> in 1967.<ref name="Bentley, 93"/> ''[[TV Century 21]]'' script editor [[Angus P. Allan]] wrote ''Introducing Captain Scarlet'', ''Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons'' and ''Captain Scarlet of Spectrum'',<ref name="Bentley, 93"/> while ''Captain Scarlet is Indestructible'' and ''Captain Scarlet versus Captain Black'' were scripted by his assistant, [[Richard O'Neill]].<ref name="Bentley, 93"/>

The first of the [[Audio theatre|audio adventure]]s, ''Introducing Captain Scarlet'', is set during the [[d<U+00E9>nouement]] to the pilot episode, "[[The Mysterons (Captain Scarlet episode)|The Mysterons]]".<ref name="Bentley, 94">Bentley, 94.</ref> The plot mainly focuses on a military conference investigating the events of the episode,<ref name="Bentley, 94"/> with the inclusion of audio [[Flashback (narrative)|flashbacks]] to provide [[Exposition (literary technique)|exposition]].<ref name="Bentley, 94"/> At the conclusion to the adventure, it is revealed that the [[Mysteron]] duplicate of [[Captain Scarlet (character)|Captain Scarlet]] has returned to life and that Scarlet's loyalty to Spectrum can be restored with the aid of the advanced computer which appeared in the Andersons' pilot script for "The Mysterons".<ref name="Bentley, 94"/>

===Books and comics===
In the late 1960s, three [[tie-in]] novels were published under the name of "John Theydon", pseudonymous for author John William Jennison,<ref name="Bentley, 109">Bentley, 109.</ref> and are titled ''Captain Scarlet and the Mysterons'' (1967), ''Captain Scarlet and the Silent Saboteur'' (1967) and ''The Angels and the Creeping Enemy'' (1968).<ref name="Titles">All titles as published in ''The Complete Book of Captain Scarlet'' (2001), by Chris Bentley, pp. 109<U+2013>11.</ref><ref name="SHBooksComics">{{cite web|last=Bishop|first=Chris|title=Merchandising: Books & Magazines|url=http://www.spectrum-headquarters.com/books.html|work=''spectrum-headquarters.com''|date=25 February 2008|accessdate=6 November 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080612175958/http://www.spectrum-headquarters.com/books.html|archivedate=12 June 2008|deadurl=no}}</ref> As the name implies, the third of the novels concentrates mainly on the characters of the Spectrum Angels as the primary protagonists.<ref name="SHBooksComics"/> Later, in 1993, Young [[Random House|Corgi Books]] published four [[novelisation]]s, targeted at children, based upon the original series episodes "[[The Mysterons (Captain Scarlet episode)|The Mysterons]]", "[[Lunarville 7]]", "[[Noose of Ice]]" and "[[The Launching]]".<ref name="SHBooksComics"/>

''Captain Scarlet'' also formed the basis of three [[comic strip]]s drawn for the weekly Anderson-related children's comic ''[[TV Century 21]]''.<ref name="Bentley, 102"/> Spanning 17 issues (numbers 141<U+2013>157) from September 1967 to January 1968, the strip adventures were written by [[Angus P. Allan]], with artwork by [[Ron Embleton]], and were titled ''We Will Destroy Unity City'', ''We Will Destroy the Observatory Network'' and ''We Shall Make Earth a Planet of Silence''.<ref name="Bentley, 102"/> After the television series ended its original run, the comic continued the story of the ''Captain Scarlet'' universe, depicting the [[Mysteron]]s deactivating their [[Mars|Martian]] computer complex and relinquishing their control of [[Captain Black (Captain Scarlet)|Captain Black]], and [[Captain Scarlet (character)|Scarlet]] himself quitting Spectrum to use his powers in the fight against [[Earth]]-bound criminals and threats.<ref name="Drake and Bassett, 280"/> The Mysterons ultimately re-awaken, prompting Scarlet and Spectrum to resume their struggle.<ref name="Drake and Bassett, 280"/>

A [[manga]] adaptation of the series, titled ''Captain Scarlet'', also ran in the Japanese ''[[Sh<U+014D>nen Book]]'' anthology from January to August 1968.<ref name="SHManga">{{cite web|last=Bishop|first=Chris|title=Cast of Characters: Captain Scarlet|url=http://www.spectrum-headquarters.com/captain_scarlet.html|work=''spectrum-headquarters.com''|date=26 July 2005|accessdate=6 November 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080612171939/http://www.spectrum-headquarters.com/captain_scarlet.html|archivedate=12 June 2008|deadurl=no}}</ref> Meanwhile, Century 21 released [[Annual publication|annuals]] based on ''Captain Scarlet'' from 1967 to 1969,<ref name="SHBooksComics"/> and the original comic strips reappeared in the ''TV21 Annual'' in 1968 and 1969.<ref name="SHBooksComics"/> Additional annuals, published in 1993 and 1994 by Grandreams,<ref name="SHBooksComics"/> accompanied the revived [[BBC2]] broadcasts of the original episodes,<ref name="SHBooksComics"/> before [[Carlton Books]] released a 2002 edition complementing the digitally [[remaster]]ed transmissions which started in 2001.<ref name="SHBooksComics"/>

===Video and DVD===
In the United Kingdom, ''Captain Scarlet'' has received a number of [[home video]] releases in the VHS format. [[Carlton Video]] released the series, both in eight individual volumes and as a "Complete Series [[Box Set]]",<ref name="Bentley, 128">Bentley, 128.</ref><ref name="SHVideos">{{cite web|last=Bishop|first=Chris|title=Merchandising<U+2014>Multimedias: Videos|url=http://www.spectrum-headquarters.com/videos.html|work=''spectrum-headquarters.com''|date=19 May 2002|accessdate=22 November 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080510221300/http://www.spectrum-headquarters.com/videos.html|archivedate=10 May 2008|deadurl=no}}</ref> from September 2001 to March 2002.<ref name="Bentley, 128"/><ref name="SHVideos"/> Presented with the [[remaster]]ed image and audio quality introduced for the 2001 [[BBC Two]] repeat transmissions,<ref name="Bentley, 125"/> the box set includes a ninth tape containing ''The Indestructible Captain Scarlet'', a programme which offers an overview of Spectrum, the [[Mysteron]]s and the events of ''Captain Scarlet''.<ref name="SHVideos"/> Earlier releases, marketed by [[PolyGram]] and "Channel 5",<ref name="SHVideos"/> had presented the episodes in a different order from the original broadcasts<ref name="SHVideos"/> and, in the case of the first two volumes, added to them with the insertion of specially-filmed footage for the 1980s [[ITC Entertainment|ITC]] releases of the ''Captain Scarlet'' [[compilation film]]s.<ref name="SHVideos"/>

Since September 2001, ''Captain Scarlet'' has also been available on [[PAL]] [[DVD region code|Region]] 2 DVD in five instalments, also from Carlton,<ref name="SHDVD"/><ref name="Bentley, 128"/> which feature [[Dolby]] 5.1 [[Surround Sound]] to replace the original [[Monaural|mono]] track.<ref name="SHDVD"/><ref name="DVDDetails">{{cite web|last=LeVasseur|first=Andrea|title=''Captain Scarlet'' Region 1 DVD Release Information|url=http://www.allmovie.com/dvd/captain-scarlet-4-discs-25250|work=''[[Allmovie]]''|accessdate=22 October 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5m03OjHAV|archivedate=13 December 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> Special features for these releases include [[Audio commentary|audio commentaries]] from [[Gerry Anderson]] for the episodes "[[The Mysterons (Captain Scarlet episode)|The Mysterons]]" and "[[Attack on Cloudbase]]", the five tie-in [[Audio theatre|audio adventures]] from 1967, behind-the-scenes production photos and information on original ITC publicity and [[merchandise]], and [[TV spot]]s from the 1960s.<ref name="SHDVD"/> As is the case for the VHS editions, the five volumes have been also been released together as a "Complete Series Box Set", containing an additional sixth disc which includes ''Captain Scarlet S.I.G.''<ref name="DVDSubs">{{cite web|title=''Captain Scarlet'' Region 2 DVD Release Information|url=http://dvd-subtitles.com/captain-scarlet-and-the-mysterons-the-complete-series-box-set-d3970.html|work=''dvd-subtitles.com''|date=30 December 2005|accessdate=22 November 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5m03GX98K|archivedate=13 December 2009|deadurl=yes}}</ref> (a behind-the-scenes documentary produced and presented by Gerry Anderson) and five sets of alternative [[opening credits]].<ref name="SHDVD"/>

A four-disc [[NTSC]] North American Region 1 edition of the box set, released by [[A&E Television Networks|A&E Home Video]] in 2002,<ref name="Billboard"/><ref name="DVDDetails"/> contains much the same special features as its Region 2 counterpart with the exception of a text-based "Introduction to Captain Scarlet" and items of DVD-ROM material.<ref name="DVDDetails"/><ref name="DigiMonkey">{{cite web|title=Digital Monkey Box Presents ''Captain Scarlet''|url=http://www.digitalmonkeybox.com/captain_scarlet.htm|work=''digitalmonkeybox.com''|accessdate=22 November 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20071115090623/http://digitalmonkeybox.com/captain_scarlet.htm|archivedate=15 November 2007|deadurl=no}}</ref> In 2004, Imavision unveiled an alternative French-language edition of the box set aimed at the Canadian market.<ref name="SHDVD"/> The set is also available in Japan on Region 2 (as six discs)<ref name="SHDVD"/> and Australia on Region 4 (as five discs).<ref name="SHDVD"/>

==Later productions==
Distribution rights to much of the [[ITC Entertainment]] catalogue have been transferred since the 1980s, initially to [[PolyGram|PolyGram Entertainment]],<ref name="Transdiffusion">{{cite web|last=Buxton|first=Roddy|title=Cinema for Television|date=5 February 2008|url=http://www.transdiffusion.org/emc/behindthescreens/cinema_for_tele.php|work=''transdiffusion.org''|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080604104428/www.transdiffusion.org/emc/behindthescreens/cinema_for_tele.php|archivedate=4 June 2008|accessdate=12 April 2010}}</ref><ref name="BFIDistribution">{{cite web|title=British Film and TV Rights and Distribution Histories|date=5 May 2009|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/filmtvinfo/researchers/distribution/british.html|work=''[[British Film Institute|BFI]] [[screenonline]]''|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080822071937/http://www.bfi.org.uk/filmtvinfo/researchers/distribution/british.html|archivedate=22 August 2008|accessdate=12 April 2010}}</ref><ref name="Archer and Hearn, 260">Archer and Hearn, 260.</ref> (or "PolyGram Television")<ref name="BFIDistribution"/> then [[Carlton Communications|Carlton International]] in the late 1990s<ref name="Transdiffusion"/><ref name="BBCCarlton">{{cite web|title=''Captain Scarlet'' Without Strings|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/841549.stm|work=''[[BBC News Online]]''|date=19 July 2000|accessdate=6 November 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20030409232216/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/841549.stm|archivedate=9 April 2003|deadurl=no}}</ref> after a partial sale to the [[BBC]] in 1991.<ref name="Archer and Hearn, 260"/> In 2004, Carlton International merged into [[Granada International]],<ref name="BFIDistribution"/> the current rights holder,<ref name="Transdiffusion"/> which in 2008 was renamed ITV Global Entertainment,<ref name="BFIDistribution"/> a division of [[ITV plc]].<ref name="BFIDistribution"/> [[Theatrical release]] rights are held by [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] (MGM).<ref name="Transdiffusion"/> In addition to other projects, [[Gerry Anderson]] announced plans for a live-action film adaptation of ''Captain Scarlet'' in 2000<ref name="SHADO-USECC">{{cite journal|last=Martin|first=Marc|month=April|year=2001|title=An American ''UFO'' Fan Goes to 'Century 21'|journal=Communiqu<U+00E9> Newsletter|issue=92|publisher=Official American ''UFO'' Fan Club|url=http://ufoseries.com/conventions/c21Report.html|accessdate=6 November 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080207064026/http://ufoseries.com/conventions/c21Report.html|archivedate=7 February 2008|deadurl=no}}</ref> and again in 2002<ref name="THound02">{{cite web|url=http://www.toonhound.com/oct2002.htm|title=The Hound<U+2014>October 2002: ''Thunderbirds'' Not So FAB?|work=''toonhound.com''|date=8 October 2002|accessdate=22 November 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080421161821/http://www.toonhound.com/oct2002.htm|archivedate=21 April 2008|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="THound03">{{cite web|url=http://www.toonhound.com/april2003.htm|title=The Hound<U+2014>April 2003: ''Scarlet'' in the Red|work=''toonhound.com''|date=28 April 2003|accessdate=26 November 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080410022147/http://www.toonhound.com/april2003.htm|archivedate=10 April 2008|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="THound05">{{cite web|url=http://www.toonhound.com/sept2005.htm|title=The Hound<U+2014>September 2005: Thunder in the Air|work=''toonhound.com''|date=18 September 2005|accessdate=22 November 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080420161628/http://www.toonhound.com/sept2005.htm|archivedate=20 April 2008|deadurl=no}}</ref> during the production of the [[Thunderbirds (film)|''Thunderbirds'' film]] released in 2004, but the idea has not been developed since.

===Compilation films===
{{Main|Captain Scarlet vs the Mysterons|Revenge of the Mysterons from Mars}}

In 1980, the New York offices of ITC, under the supervision of [[Robert Mandell]],<ref name="Bentley, 121">Bentley, 121.</ref> combined episodes from the original series to make two [[compilation film]]s for American audiences, with the aim of reviving transatlantic [[Broadcast syndication|syndication]] sales.<ref name="Bentley, 121"/> This became common practice for Anderson productions during the 1980s, with [[made-for-television]] films comprising episodes of ''[[Stingray (TV series)|Stingray]]'' and ''[[Thunderbirds (TV series)|Thunderbirds]]'' airing to US [[Cable television in the United States|cable]] audiences under the generic promotional banner of "Super Space Theater".<ref name="Bentley: Episode Guide, 361">Bentley: ''Episode Guide'', 361.</ref> On 24 November 1988, the second ''Captain Scarlet'' film, ''[[Revenge of the Mysterons from Mars]]'', was broadcast as the second episode of the American television series ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]'', from [[Minneapolis]], on station [[KTMA]].

===CGI test film and series===
{{Main|Gerry Anderson's New Captain Scarlet}}

In 1999, [[Gerry Anderson]] supervised the production of a short [[computer-animated]] test film, ''Captain Scarlet and the Return of the Mysterons'', to explore the possibility of updating a number of his 1960s [[Supermarionation]] series for a 21st-century audience.<ref name="Bentley, 123">Bentley, 123.</ref><ref name="Teletronic5">{{cite web|last=Marcus|first=Laurence|title=Gerry Anderson: The Puppet Master<U+2014>Part 5|url=http://www.teletronic.co.uk/gerryanderson5.htm|work=''teletronic.co.uk''|year=2006|month=June|accessdate=22 November 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20071030130851/http://www.teletronic.co.uk/gerryanderson5.htm|archivedate=30 October 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> The [[working title]] was ''Captain Scarlet<U+2014>The New Millennium''.<ref name="Teletronic5"/> Produced in London by the [[Moving Picture Company]],<ref name="Bentley, 123"/> the film features [[Francis Matthews (actor)|Francis Matthews]] and [[Ed Bishop]] reprising the roles of Captains [[Captain Scarlet (character)|Scarlet]] and [[Captain Blue (Captain Scarlet)|Blue]].<ref name="ToonhoundEntry"/><ref name="Teletronic5"/> Made using a combination of [[Autodesk Maya|Maya]] 3D computer graphics software and [[motion-capture]] technology,<ref name="Bentley, 124">Bentley, 124.</ref><ref name="Teletronic5"/> the plot commences a few years after the [[Mysteron]]s end their hostilities against [[Earth]], but the reappearance of [[Captain Black (Captain Scarlet)|Captain Black]] sets the stage for a revival of the war with [[Mars]].<ref name="Bentley, 124"/> Although the film has yet to receive a [[home video]] release, it was publicly screened at a [[Fanderson]] convention in 2000<ref name="Bentley, 125"/><ref name="SHADO-USECC"/><ref name="Teletronic5"/> and at a science lecture in 2001.<ref name="Bentley, 125"/>

Plans for a full CGI ''Captain Scarlet'' television series to follow the test film finally resulted in ''Gerry Anderson's New Captain Scarlet''. A [[Reboot (fiction)|reboot]] of the original series, this was first broadcast in the United Kingdom on the Saturday-morning [[CITV]] programme, ''[[Ministry of Mayhem]]'', from 12 February 2005.<ref name="Bentley: Episode Guide, 282">Bentley: ''Episode Guide'', 282.</ref> Produced by "Anderson Entertainment" and the "Indestructible Production Company",<ref name="Teletronic5"/><ref name="Bentley: Episode Guide, 281">Bentley: ''Episode Guide'', 281.</ref> the animation used to create the series is billed in the credits as "[[Hypermarionation]]"<ref name="Bentley: Episode Guide, 281"/> to acknowledge the 1960s puppet technique, Supermarionation.<ref name="Bentley: Episode Guide, 281"/>

